 Residents who are eligible for a special vote will make their mark on the ballot paper today and tomorrow, before the rest of the country heads to the polls on May 8. At 75, Anna Nkomo voted in the comfort of her home in Rockville, Mhluzi. Anna Nkomo. The witty Gogo was determined to vote regardless of her painful ankle, “My voice will be heard and the only way to do so is by voting,” said Ms Nkomo.
She told the IEC officials that she has never missed the opportunity to vote since 1994, she also urged other residents to vote. Lilly Nhlapo (89) also practised her democratic right, the excited granny needed no assistance voting for her party of choice, she praised officials for coming to her home as she is unable to walk long distances. Lilly Nhlapo. No one was left behind as visually impaired Lizzy Mahlangu (62) also got an opportunity to decide the direction of the country, she expressed satisfaction after casting her vote. Lizzy Mahlanga. Of course the day had slight setbacks as Annaie Mthombeni (90) only had her Apartheid pass book instead of her green book. Her granddaughter left with her ID, Ms Mthombeni will vote either today or tomorrow.     Parents frustrated by a lack of space in Middelburg schools Traffic officers to appear in court for corruption #TrafficAlert: Two dead in Kranspoort accidents VIDEO: Two perish after truck jack-knifes • Save our standby number (072 248 3855) and send us a WhatsApp message with the words “Add me” to be added to our broadcast list. • Like us on Facebook, follow us on Twitter and Instagram. • Subscribe to our YouTube channel. • Click on the link to subscribe to our bi-weekly newsletter via email. Contact our news room on our 24 hr standby number 072 248 3855, or send a mail to our editor tobie@mobserver.co.za